DDL(Data Definition Language) Commands

DDL or Data Definition Language actually consists of the SQL commands that can be used to define the database schema. It simply deals with descriptions of the database schema and is used to create and modify the structure of database objects in the database.

Create Table

xxxxxxxxxx
6
1
CREATE TABLE employee (
2
    empId INT ,
3
    empName VARCHAR(50),
4
    joining DATE,
5
    salary INT
6
);

Following are the data types available in SQL:

VARCHAR(size) : To define a string of max ‘size’ characters.

INT/INTEGER/NUMBER: To define an integer

FLOAT/DOUBLE: To define a decimal point number.

DATE: To define a date

BLOB/CLOB: Large Object Files used to store large data that are usually in GBs

 

ALTER Table

  1. ADD :-

    ADD is used to add a new column in a table .

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    ALTER TABLE employee ADD dept VARCHAR(30);
    2
    ALTER TABLE Student ADD (AGE number(3),COURSE varchar(40));

     

  2. MODIFY :-

    MODIFY is used to change the column definition of the table.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    3
    1
    ALTER TABLE table_name MODIFY column_name column_definition;
    2
    ALTER TABLE EMPLOYEE MODIFY EmpName VARCHAR(20);
    3
    ALTER TABLE EMPLOYEE MODIFY EmpName VARCHAR(20) NOT NULL;

     

  3. DROP COLUMN :-

    DROP COLUMN is used for deleting a column from the table.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    ALTER TABLE table_name DROP COLUMN column_name; 
    2
    ALTER TABLE EMPLOYEE DROP COLUMN salary;

     

  4. RENAME COLUMN :-

    RENAME is used to rename a column.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    ALTER TABLE table_name RENAME COLUMN old_column_name TO new_column_name;
    2
    ALTER TABLE EMPLOYEE RENAME COLUMN phone TO mobile_no;

     

  5. RENAME TO :-

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    ALTER TABLE existing_table RENAME TO new_table;
    2
    ALTER TABLE  employee RENAME TO emp_data;

     

  6. DROP TABLE :-

    DROP TABLE is used to remove an entire table including all of its data and metadata.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    DROP TABLE <table_name>;
    2
    DROP TABLE employee;

     

  7. TRUNCATE TABLE :-

    Sometimes, according to requirements one may want to delete all the table data kept in the table. One way is to drop the table. But in that case the structure of the table is also deleted. It’ll have to be created again with the CREATE TABLE command. Another way is to use the DELETE statement. However, when having a table with a large number of rows, using the DELETE statement to remove all data is not efficient. But TRUNCATE TABLE statement that allows to delete all rows from a big table efficiently. On using this command , we can't recover removed data records using rollback or any other undo operation.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    TRUNCATE TABLE table_name;  # TRUNCATE must be in capital

    SELECT with Logical Operators :-

    The following are the different types of logical operators

    AND : Multiple conditions can be defined in SQL statements and it will return records only when all the defined conditions are true.

    OR : Multiple conditions can be defined in SQL statements and it will return records if any one of defined conditions is true.

    IN : By using IN operator it can be checked if a given value exists in the list of values or in the subquery result set.

    NOT IN : It’s just opposite to the IN operator. By using the NOT IN operator it can be checked if a given value exists in the list of values or in the subquery result set.

    BETWEEN : We can return values which exist between a defined range of values.

    EXISTS : By using EXISTS we can check whether the required value exists in the result set or not

    IN Operator

    The SQL IN operator determines whether a value matches any value in a list or a subquery. The syntax of the IN operator is as follows:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select column1,column2...columnN from table_name where col_name_to_be_checked [NOT] IN (value_list|subquery);

    A list of values is a fixed value list or a result set of a single column returned by a subquery. The returned type of expression and values in the list must be the same.

    The IN operator returns true or false depending on whether the expression matches any value in a list of values or not. To negate the list of values, you use the NOT IN operator.

    For Example we want to find the employees who work in either the HR department or the Admin Department, query will be formed as follows:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select * from employee where DEPT IN ('HR','Admin');

    BETWEEN Operator

    The BETWEEN operator is a logical operator that tests whether a value is in range of values. If the value is in the specified range, the BETWEEN operator returns true. The BETWEEN operator can be used in the WHERE clause of the SELECT, DELETE, UPDATE, and REPLACE statements.

    The following illustrates the syntax of the SQL BETWEEN operator:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select column1,column2...columnN from table_name where col_name_to_be_checked BETWEEN low_expression AND high_expression

    In this syntax:

    • low_expression and high_expression is any valid expression that specify the low and high values of the range. The low_expression should be less than or equal to high_expression, or the BETWEEN is always returns false.
    • The AND keyword is a placeholder which indicates the test_expression should be within the range specified by low_expression and high_expression.
    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select * from employee where SALARY BETWEEN 20000 AND 40000;

    Select with LIKE Operators

    In SQL, LIKE operator is used to check whether the given string value matches with specific pattern or not. In case if string value matches with pattern value then it will return true.

    In SQL, LIKE operator is case insensitive, so 'a' LIKE 'A' is true and all non-NULL parameter expressions will be converted to text values. 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    SELECT column1,column2..columnN FROM table_name WHERE expression LIKE pattern;

    In above SQL LIKE syntax,

    expression is the character expression such as a column or field.

    pattern is the character expression that contains pattern matching.

    In SQL,LIKE operator pattern syntax supports two wildcards. 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    % allows you to match any string of any length (including zero-length).
    2
    _  allows you to match on a single character.

    The following details give an idea to use Like operator with wildcard characters %, _ to get records from tables.

    Where name LIKE ‘a%’ - It returns all the records whose name starts with ‘a’

    Where name LIKE ‘%b’ - It returns all the records whose name ends with ‘b’

    Where name LIKE ‘%c%’ - It returns all the records whose name contains ‘c’ character

    Where name LIKE ‘Dav_’ - It returns records whose name starts with ‘Dav’ and contains 4 characters

    Where name LIKE ‘_a%’ - It returns records whose name contains the second character as ‘a’ and it should contain a minimum of 2 characters.

SQL CONTRAINTS

Constraints can be specified when the table is created with the CREATE TABLE statement, or after the table is created with the ALTER TABLE statement.

xxxxxxxxxx
6
1
CREATE TABLE table_name (
2
    column1 datatype constraint,
3
    column2 datatype constraint,
4
    column3 datatype constraint,
5
    ....
6
);
  • NOT NULL - Ensures that a column cannot have a NULL value
  • UNIQUE - Ensures that all values in a column are different OR It is used to set restriction on a column to allow only unique values in the column.
  • PRIMARY KEY - A combination of a NOT NULL and UNIQUE. Uniquely identifies each row(record) in a table. There can be more UNIQUE columns, but only one primary key in a table.
  • FOREIGN KEY - Prevents actions that would destroy links between tables
  • CHECK - Ensures that the values in a column satisfies a specific condition
  • DEFAULT - Sets a default value for a column if no value is specified

Just like other constraints UNIQUE constraints can be added while creating the table or After the table is created using an ALTER statement.

    The UNIQUE constraint is a column constraint. And it can be used to enforce the unique rule for one column.

  3. PRIMARY KEY :-

    Note: A table can have only ONE primary key; and in the table, this primary key can consist of single or multiple columns (fields).A primary Key cannot have more that 32 columns included in it.

    A primary key can be created while creating a table as follows

  4. FOREIGN KEY :-

    The FOREIGN KEY constraint is used to prevent actions that would destroy links between tables.

    A FOREIGN KEY is a field (or collection of fields) in one table, that refers to the PRIMARY KEY in another table.

    The table with the foreign key is called the child table, and the table with the primary key is called the referenced or parent table. The FOREIGN KEY constraint prevents invalid data from being inserted into the foreign key column, because it has to be one of the values contained in the parent table.

    Create a Department table with columns id as PRIMARY KEY & dept. name. & insert the data

    xxxxxxxxxx
    3
    1
    CREATE TABLE dept(ID INT PRIMARY KEY,Deptname VARCHAR(50));
    2
    INSERT INTO dept VALUES(1,'ADMIN');
    3
    INSERT INTO dept VALUES(2,'HR');

    Create a table employee with columns emp's ID, name, & dept.id as foreign key.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    CREATE TABLE employee(EmpID INT,Empname VARCHAR(50),DeptID INT,FOREIGN KEY(DeptId) REFERENCES dept(ID));

    Query:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    INSERT INTO employee VALUES(1,'Rohit',3);

    Output:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    ORA-02291: integrity constraint (SYSTEM.SYS_C006988) violated - parent key not found
    xxxxxxxxxx
    12
    1
    /* Create the tables `dept` and `students` as per given task */

    create table dept(
    3

  5. CHECK :-

    CHECK Constraint is used to define specific conditions on a column to validate those conditions while inserting or updating the data in table columns.

    Check Constraint can be added while creating a table or it can be added at a later time by ALTER statement

    To create a check constraint at the time of creation of table,

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    CREATE TABLE books(Book_id INT,bookName VARCHAR(50) ,PRICE INT, CONSTRAINT price_chk CHECK (PRICE > 0));

    OR The following query can also be used to add a check constraint while creation of the table. 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    CREATE TABLE books(Book_id INT,bookName VARCHAR(50) ,price INT CHECK (PRICE > 0));

    In the first query ,a constraint named ‘price_chk’ is created on the table books while creating the table. In the second example, the constraint name isn't provided , the database will provide the name like SYSTEM.SYS_C006987.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    4
    1
    -- Another Example
    2
    CREATE TABLE books(Book_id INT,bookName VARCHAR(50) ,PRICE INT );
    3
    ALTER TABLE books ADD CONSTRAINT priceCheck CHECK (PRICE > 0);
    4
    -- In this , a constraint named ‘priceCheck’ is created on the table after the creation of the table using ALTER Statement.

    If the constraint is violated the database will throw an error as follows:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    ORA-02290: check constraint (SYSTEM.PRICECHECK) violated

     

  6. DEFAULT :-

    Default Constraint is used to define default values for a column. Default constraint will insert default value in a column in case if the column value is null or empty while inserting data into the table.

    The default value will be added to all new records IF no other value is specified.

    Just like the check constraint DEFAULT constraint can also be added during the creation of table or afterwards by using the ALTER statement.

    To add a DEFAULT constraint at the time of creation,

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    CREATE TABLE books(Book_id INT, bookName VARCHAR(50) , PRICE INT DEFAULT 500);

    OR To add the constraint at a later time

    xxxxxxxxxx
    2
    1
    CREATE TABLE books(Book_id INT, bookName VARCHAR(50) , PRICE INT);
    2
    ALTER TABLE books MODIFY PRICE DEFAULT 500;

 

Clauses

  1. GROUP BY :-

    The SQL GROUP BY clause is used with the SELECT statement to collaborate the same identical elements into groups.

    The GROUP BY clause is used with WHERE clause in the SELECT statement and precedes the ORDER BY clause

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    SELECT column-list FROM table_name WHERE [ conditions ] GROUP BY column1, column2....columnN;

    Example :- 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select Dept,COUNT(EmpID) from employee group by dept;

    In the above query, we use the COUNT function to count the number of employees. The group by clause groups all the records together that are in the same department and the count function returns the number of EmpID's that are present in the particular group.

    Output :-

    Example 2 :-

    Q. Write a query to display all the student’s department (stud_dept) as 'dept' followed by the count of students as 'cnt' in that particular department.

    Ans :- 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select stud_dept "dept",COUNT(roll_no) "cnt" from students GROUP BY stud_dept;

     

  2. HAVING :-

    The SQL HAVING clause is used to specify conditions that filter which group results appear in the final results. The WHERE clause places conditions on the selected columns, whereas the HAVING clause places conditions on groups created by the GROUP BY clause.

    HAVING clause is often used with the GROUP BY clause. The GROUP BY clause groups a set of rows into a set of summary rows or groups. Then the HAVING clause filters groups based on a specified condition.

    Syntax:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    SELECT column1_list FROM table_name WHERE [ conditions ] GROUP BY column_name HAVING [ conditions ];

    While using the HAVING clause, GROUP BY clause must be included; otherwise, the following error will pop-up;

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    Error: a GROUP BY clause is required before HAVING

    Example :-

    Query :- 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select Dept,COUNT(EmpID) from employee group by dept having dept='HR';

    Output :-

    Note: We can use logical operators in having clause just the same way it is used in the where clause.

    Example 2 :-

    Q. Write a query to display the stud_dept as 'dept' followed by the count of the students of the ‘CSE’ and ‘Mechanical’ department as 'cnt'.

    Ans :- 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select stud_dept "dept",COUNT(roll_no) "cnt" from students GROUP BY stud_dept HAVING stud_dept='CSE' OR stud_dept='Mechanical';

     

  3. ORDER BY :-

    The SQL ORDER BY clause is used to sort the fetched data in ascending or descending order, based on one or more columns.

    The ORDER BY clause comes after the FROM clause. It allows you to sort the result set based on one or more columns in ascending or descending order.

    In the below syntax, place the column name which is to be sorted after the ORDER BY clause followed by the ASC or DESC keyword.

    • The ASC keyword means ascending.
    • And the DESC keyword means descending.

    If it isn’t specified through the ASC or DESC keyword, SQL sorts the result set using the ASC option. In other words, it sorts the result set in the ascending order by default.

    To sort the result set by multiple columns, use a comma (,) to separate two columns. The ORDER BY clause sorts rows using columns or expressions from left to right. In other words, the ORDER BY clause sorts the rows using the first column in the list. Then, it sorts the sorted rows using the second column, and so on.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    SELECT column-list FROM table_name [WHERE condition] [ORDER BY column1,column2,..columnN] [ASC | DESC];

    Example :- 

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select * from employee order by EmpName;

    Output:

    Example 2 :-

    Q. Display all the records of the table in ascending order of the student’s names.

    Ans :-

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select * from students ORDER BY stud_name;

 

Aggregate Functions :-

  1. MAX / MIN :-

    The min() aggregate function returns the minimum non-NULL value of all values in the group. The minimum value is the first non-NULL value that would appear in an ORDER BY of the column. The function returns NULL if and only if there are no non-NULL values in the group.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    Select MIN(expression) from table_name where [Conditions];

     

    The max() aggregate function returns the maximum value of all values in the group. The maximum value is the value that would be returned last in an ORDER BY on the same column. The function returns NULL if and only if there are no non-NULL values in the group.

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    Select MAX(expression) from table_name where [Conditions];

    Example :-

    Query:

    xxxxxxxxxx
    1
    1
    select MAX(SALARY),MIN(SALARY) from employee;

    Output:

     

  2. COUNT :-

    In SQL Count() Function is an aggregate function that is used to return the total number of rows in a table based on the specified expression or conditions. SQL Count() function will work with non-NULL numeric values to return a number of times non-NULL values exist in columns based on defined expressions.

    In Count() function, if we define the expression as an asterisk character (*) then the COUNT function will return the number of rows in the table based on the defined aggregate group or condition.

    We can use the where clause while using the COUNT function also.

    Example :-

    Query:

  3. Sum & Avg functions :-

    The SUM function is an aggregate function that returns the sum of the non-NULL values or only the distinct values in a group.

    The result of the SUM function is an integer if all input non-NULL values are integers. If any input value is neither an integer nor a NULL value, the result of the SUM function is a floating-point value.

    The result of the SUM function is NULL if and only if all input values are NULL.

    The AVG function is an aggregate function that calculates the average value of all non-NULL values within a group.

    The value of the AVG function is always a floating-point value or a NULL value. The AVG function only returns a NULL value if and only if all values in the group are NULL values.

SQL JOINS

A JOIN clause is used to combine rows from two or more tables, based on a related column between them.

Different Types of SQL JOINs

Here are the different types of the JOINs in SQL:

  • cross JOIN: Returns the Cartesian product of rows by matching each row of the first table with every row of the second table.

  • (INNER) JOIN: Returns records that have matching values in both tables

  • LEFT (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records from the left table, and the matched records from the right table

  • RIGHT (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records from the right table, and the matched records from the left table

  • FULL (OUTER) JOIN: Returns all records when there is a match in either left or right table

 

CROSS JOIN

CROSS JOIN is used to get the Cartesian product of rows by matching each row of the first table with every row of the second table.

Cross join resultant table will contain multiplication number of rows in input tables. Suppose if table1 contains 10 rows and table2 contains 5 rows then if we apply Cross Join on these two tables we will get a resultant table that contains 50 rows.

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 CROSS JOIN table_name_2 [WHERE conditions];

Example :-

Employee table

 

Department table

 

Query:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
select * from employee cross join department;

INNER JOIN

The INNER JOIN returns only the rows that match the join condition and eliminate all other rows that don't match the join condition.

The INNER JOIN clause returns rows from the first table that has the corresponding row in the second table. The same logic is applied when more than one table is joined.

Its Syntax is a follows:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 INNER JOIN table_name_2 ON [table_name_1.column_name=table_name_2.column_name and ...] [WHERE conditions];

While using inner joins , it is necessary to specify on which column the columns must be joined. The columns which are equated should have the same datatype in their respective definitions.

Example :-

Employee table

 

Department table

Query:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
select * from employee inner join department on employee.emp_dept=department.dept_id;

Output :-

The INNER JOIN works as following:

  • The INNER JOIN clause is written after the first table is referenced with the "From" clause.

  • The join condition is specified with ‘ON’.

  • The INNER word is optional, you can just write JOIN. In short, Inner Join is the default keyword for Join and both can be used interchangeably.

  • The INNER JOIN produces the records from both - the employee’s and the department's tables that match the condition which is “employee.emp_dept = department.dept_Id ". The unmatched rows will be ignored and not included in the result.

  • Notice that the employee with ‘emp_id’ 1003 isn’t present in the output table because the ‘emp_dept’ value of the employee was empty or we can say NULL.

LEFT OUTER JOIN / LEFT JOIN

By using Inner Join we can get only matching rows from multiple tables based on the conditions defined in select statements. SQL Outer Join will select matching rows from multiple tables same as Inner Join and some other rows outside of the relationship.

The SQL LEFT Outer JOIN joins two tables and fetches rows based on a condition, which is matching in both the tables and the unmatched rows from the ‘left’ will also be available from the table written before the JOIN clause.

So, in the case of LEFT JOIN or LEFT OUTER JOIN, SQL -

  1. Takes all selected values from the left table
  2. Combines them with the column names (specified in the condition) from the right table
  3. Retrieve the matching rows from both the associated tables.
  4. Sets the value of every column from the right table to NULL which is unmatched with the left table.

Here is the basic syntax.

xxxxxxxxxx
3
1
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 LEFT OUTER JOIN table_name_2 ON table_name_1.column = table_name_2.column [WHERE CONDITIONS]
2
----------    OR     -------------
3
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 LEFT JOIN table_name_2 ON table_name_1.column = table_name_2.column [WHERE CONDITIONS]

A LEFT JOIN will preserve the records of the "left" table. SQL starts with the left table. For each row from the alias, an SQL scans the table if the condition is satisfied and returns the record. For unmatched rows, it returns null.

Example :-

Employee table

 

Department table

 

Query:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
select * from employee left outer join department on employee.emp_dept=department.dept_id;

Output:

RIGHT OUTER JOIN / RIGHT JOIN

RIGHT JOIN is the opposite of LEFT JOIN. The RIGHT JOIN returns all the columns from the table on the right even if no matching rows have been found in the table on the left. Where no matches have been found in the table on the left, NULL is returned.

So, in the case of RIGHT JOIN or RIGHT OUTER JOIN, SQL -

  1. Takes all selected values from the right table
  2. Combines them with the column names (specified in the condition) from the left table
  3. Retrieve the matching rows from both the associated tables.
  4. Sets the value of every column from the left table to NULL which is unmatched with the right table.

Syntax As follows:

xxxxxxxxxx
3
1
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 RIGHT OUTER JOIN table_name_2 ON table_name_1.column = table_name_2.column [WHERE CONDITIONS]
2
----------    OR     -------------
3
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 RIGHT JOIN table_name_2 ON table_name_1.column = table_name_2.column [WHERE CONDITIONS]

Example :-

Employee Table:

Department Table:

FULL OUTER  JOIN / FULL JOIN

A Full Outer Join is basically the combined result of inner join, left join and right join.

Suppose you have two tables table1 and table2. The following illustrates the full outer join of the two tables:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SELECT [* | select_list] FROM table1 FULL OUTER JOIN table2 ON join_condition WHERE [where_condition] ;

For each row in table1, the full outer join compares it with every row in table2.

If rows from both tables meet the join_condition, the full outer join includes columns of both rows in the result set. It can also be said that the row in table1 table matches with the row in table2 in this case.

If a row from table1 does not have any matching row from table2, the full outer join will include columns from table1 with null values for all columns from table2.

Similarly, if a row in table2 does not have a matching row in table1, the full outer join will include columns from table2 with the null values for the columns in table1.

Note that the OUTER keyword is optional, therefore, the FULL OUTER JOIN and FULL JOIN are the same.

For example, given the employee table:

And, Department Table:

The Full Outer Join will be written as :

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
select roll_no,name,marks from students full join stud_marks on students.roll_no=stud_marks.stud_roll;

Output of the above query:

NATURAL JOIN

A NATURAL JOIN is very similar to an Inner JOIN, the difference is that it automatically tests for equality between the values of every column that exists in both tables.

The difference between INNER JOIN and a NATURAL JOIN:

  • In INNER JOIN,a join condition is specified through which the inner join uses to join the two tables. Whereas in the natural join,no join condition is written.Write the two tables' names without any condition.Then the natural join will automatically test for equality between the values for every column in both tables.
  • In the NATURAL JOIN, all the columns from both tables with the same name will be matched against each other. For example, if there are two tables with two column names in common(the two columns exist with the same name in the two tables), then the natural join will join the two tables by comparing the values of both columns and not just from one column.
  • The NATURAL JOIN is structured in such a way that columns with the same name of associate tables will appear once only,unlike INNER JOIN which prints the same column twice.

Natural Join: Guidelines

To implement a natural join,there are guidelines one must follow:

  • The associated tables have one or more pairs of identically named columns.
  • The columns must be of the same data type.
  • ‘ON’ clause is never used in a NATURAL JOIN.
xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SELECT [ * | column_list ] FROM table_name_1 NATURAL JOIN table_name_2;

 

For understanding natural joins let us consider 2 tables, employee and department

Employee:

Department:

Query:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1

Note: If any columns aren’t matched, then the Natural Join clause will return the cross join of the tables.

Indexes

An index is a performance-tuning method of allowing faster retrieval of records. An index creates an entry for each value that appears in the indexed columns. By default, Oracle creates B-tree indexes.Here B-Tree stands for balanced tree not a binary tree.

Indexes are special lookup tables that the database search engine can use to speed up data retrieval. Simply put, an index is a pointer to data in a table. An index in a database is very similar to an index in the back of a book.

An index helps to speed up SELECT queries and WHERE clauses, but it slows down data input, with the UPDATE and the INSERT statements. Indexes can be created or dropped with no effect on the data.

When should indexes be avoided?

Although indexes are intended to enhance a database's performance, there are times when they should be avoided.

The following guidelines indicate when the use of an index should be reconsidered.

  • Indexes should not be used on small tables.
  • Tables that have frequent, large batch updates or insert operations.
  • Indexes should not be used on columns that contain a high number of NULL values.
  • Columns that are frequently manipulated should not be indexed.

Types of Indexes:

SINGLE COLUMN INDEXES: A single-column index is created based on only one table column. To create a single column index , the following query is used

Sequences

Sequence is a set of integers 1, 2, 3, … that are generated and supported by database systems to get unique values on demand.

  • A sequence is a user defined schema bound object that generates a sequence of numeric values.
  • Sequences are frequently used in many databases because many applications require each row in a table to contain a unique value and sequences provide an easy way to generate them.
  • The sequence of numeric values is generated in an ascending or descending order at defined intervals and can be configured to restart when exceeds max_value.

Following is the syntax for creating a sequence

xxxxxxxxxx
6
1
CREATE SEQUENCE sequence_name
2
START WITH initial_value
3
INCREMENT BY increment_value
4
MINVALUE minimum_value
5
MAXVALUE maximum_value
6
[CYCLE|NOCYCLE];

In the above syntax

  1. START WITH tells the sequence that from where to start the sequence.
  2. INCREMENT BY tells the sequence by how much to increment the value
  3. MINVALUE tells the minimum value in the sequence
  4. MAXVALUE tells the maximum value in the sequence
  5. CYCLE|NOCYCLE tells the sequence to restart the sequence when maximum value is attained. If NOCYCLE is selected it specifies that if sequence exceeds MAXVALUE value, an error will be thrown.

 

The below given example creates a sequence named ‘Employee_seq’ which starts with 1,increments by 1 and has minimum value and maximum value 1 and 1000 respectively.

Lastly NOCYCLE tells that the sequence will not restart once reached maximum value.

xxxxxxxxxx
6
1
CREATE SEQUENCE Employee_seq
2
START WITH 1
3
INCREMENT BY 1
4
MINVALUE 1
5
MAXVALUE 1000
6
NOCYCLE;

Clusters

If two or more tables are joined together on a single column and most of the time join queries are executed, at that time consider creating a cluster of these tables.

A cluster is a group of tables that share the same data blocks i.e. all the tables are physically stored together.

Clusters in SQL are used to store data that is from different tables in the same physical data blocks. They are used if records from those tables are frequently queried together. By storing the same data blocks, the number of database block reads needed to fully fill such queries decreases which improves performance.

  • Each cluster stores table data and maintains a clustered index to sort data.
  • Columns within the cluster index are called clustered keys. These determine the physical placement of rows within the cluster.
  • Cluster key is usually a foreign key of one table that references the primary key of another table in the cluster.

For example, EMPLOYEE and DEPT tables are joined on the DEPTNO column. If it is clustered then Oracle physically stores all rows for each department from both the employee and dept tables in the same data blocks.

  • Since clusters store related rows of different tables in the same data blocks, Disk I/O is reduced and access time improves for joins of clustered tables.
  • Each cluster key value is stored only once each in the cluster and the cluster index, no matter how many rows of different tables contain the value.

Therefore, less storage might be required to store related table and index data in a cluster than is necessary in non-clustered table format.

 

Following are the advantages of using a cluster:

  1. Disk I/O is reduced.
  2. Access time improves for joins of clustered tables.
  3. As all rows in clustered tables use the same columns as the common primary key, this yields storage benefit

And disadvantages:

  1. Reduces performance of INSERT statements as compared to storing the table separately with its own index.
  2. Columns that are often updated are not good candidates for cluster key.

Following is the syntax to create a cluster:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
CREATE CLUSTER Cluster_Name (<Column> <Data Type> [, <Column> <Data Type> ] ..... )

To create clustered tables. First, create a cluster and create an index on it. Then create tables in it.

For example, to create a cluster of EMPLOYEE and DEPT tables in which the DEPTNO will be the cluster key, first create the cluster by typing the following command.

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
create cluster emp_dept (deptno number(2));

Then create the index on it.

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
create index index_cluster on cluster emp_dept;

Now create table in the cluster like

xxxxxxxxxx
5
1
create table dept (deptno number(2), dname varchar2(20), loc varchar2(20))
2
cluster emp_dept (deptno);
3
 
4
create table employee (empno number(5), ename varchar2(20), sal number, deptno number)
5
cluster emp_dept (deptno);

First, the cluster is created, then the cluster key is created on the cluster key columns.

After the cluster key index is created, data can be entered into tables stored in clusters.

TCL Commands

TCL stands for Transaction Control Language.These commands are used to manage transactions in the database.A transaction is a unit of work performed in the database.Transactions are units or sequences of work accomplished in a logical order, whether in a manual fashion by a user or automatically by some sort of a database program. A transaction can have only 2 results : success and failure.

Transactions have the following four standard properties, referred to by the acronym ACID.

  • Atomicity : Ensures that all operations within the work unit are completed successfully. Otherwise, the transaction is aborted at the point of failure and all the previous operations are rolled back to their former state before the start of the transaction.
  • Consistency :Ensures that the database properly changes states upon a successfully committed transaction.
  • Isolation : Enables transactions to operate independently of and transparent to each other.
  • Durability : Ensures that the result or effect of a committed transaction persists in case of a system failure.

To control changes the following commands are used:

  1. START TRANSACTION: Used to indicate the database that the transaction has started.
  2. COMMIT: Used to save the changes done by the transaction.
  3. ROLLBACK: Used to roll back the changes done by the transaction in case of transaction failure. Restores the saved state of the database of the last COMMIT.It undo all data changes since the last COMMIT or SAVEPOINT command.
  4. SAVEPOINT: Used to create a savepoint in the transaction.A savepoint is like a checkpoint in a transaction.It partially saves the state of the database. If any failure occurs after that , the database state can be rolled back to the savepoint created.

So let's start understanding these commands in detail!

START TRANSACTION

This command gives information to the database indicating that a new transaction is started.The syntax to use this statement is:

COMMIT

COMMIT is used to save the changes in the database permanently.Once committed the changes during a transaction, it can be reverted back to the previous state. By default whenever we execute any command, whether it is DDL,DML or any Query, it is automatically committed by the database.To explicitly turn off the AUTOCOMMIT after every command use

To use the COMMIT statement following syntax is used

xxxxxxxxxx

Note that while creating or dropping any database object, the database automatically commits the changes irrespective of whether the autocommit feature is set on or not.

ROLLBACK

ROLLBACK is used to undo the changes to the previous commit or any particular savepoint created in the transaction.To undo the changes to the previous commit use the ROLLBACK command like

xxxxxxxxxx

And to undo the changes to a previously created savepoint use the ROLLBACK TO SAVEPOINT command like

It allows all statements that are executed after savepoint would be rolled back.It partially saves the state of the database till that savepoint. To create a save point use the SAVEPOINT statement:

Views

Views in SQL are a kind of virtual table. A view also has rows and columns as they are in a real table in the database. We can create a view by selecting fields from one or more tables present in the database. A View can either have all the rows of a table or specific rows based on certain conditions

Views which are kind of virtual tables, allow the users to −

  • Structure data in a way that users or classes of users find natural or intuitive.
  • Restrict access to the data such that a user can only see limited data instead of a complete table.
  • Summarize data from various tables, which can be used to generate reports.

The data of the underlying tables can be accessed through a view. The tables that the query in the view definition refers to are called base tables.

A view is useful in some cases:

  1. Views provide an abstraction layer over tables.
  2. Views can be used to encapsulate complex queries with joins to simplify the data access.

Given below are the syntax of creating different type of views:

Introduction to PL-SQL

PL/SQL is a block structured language that enables developers to combine the power of SQL with procedural statements.

All the statements of a block are passed to an Oracle Engine all at once which increases processing speed and decreases the traffic.

Features of PL/SQL

Following is a list of PL/SQL features which makes it different from SQL:-

  • PL/SQL is basically a procedural language which provides the functionality of :
  1. Decision-Making
  2. Iteration
  3. And many other features
  • PL/SQL can execute a no. of queries in one block using a single command.
  1. One can create a PL/SQL unit such as procedures, functions, packages, triggers which are stored in a database for reuse by application.
  2. PL/SQL provides a feature to handle the exception which occurs in the PL/SQL block known as exception handling block.
  3. PL/SQL offers extensive error checking.

Different Sections in a PL/SQL block

 

DECLARATION SECTION:

It is an Optional part.This section is used for declaring variables ,cursor’s exception and subprograms that are needed in the block.It starts with keyword “DECLARE” and is followed by Execution Section

 

EXECUTION SECTION:

It is the Main and Mandatory Part. It executes the code written inside it. It can’t be empty so it should have 1 valid executable code line in it.It contains PL/SQL and SQL Code.This block can contain one or more execution blocks.It should start with the keyword “BEGIN” and end with the “END” keyword.

 

EXCEPTION HANDLING SECTION

The exception is unavoidable in the program which occurs at run time that is handled by the exception handling section in the block. It is also optional part of PL/SQL program.The control from this section can never return to an Execution Block.

DIFFERENCES between PL/SQL and SQL

Following is the list of Differences between SQL and PL/SQL.

 

Identifiers in PL/SQL

Type and Rowtype

%TYPE

Used to declare a field or variable with the same type as that of specified field in Tables Column. %TYPE is used to declare variables with relation to the data type of a column in an existing table. The benefit here is that if the data type changes, the variable data type stays in sync.

Below given is the syntax to declare a variable using %type attribute.

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
variable_name table_name.column_name %type

Given below is an example on how to use the %type attribute while declaring any variable.

xxxxxxxxxx
8
1
-- Table emp already created
2

3
    emp1 emp.empno %type;
4
BEGIN
5
    Select empno into emp1 from emp where ename = 'KING';

7
END;
8
/

In the example, the block declares a variable of the same datatype as of empno present in the emp table.Then it is used to fetch the value in the emp1 variable using the select statement.

%ROWTYPE

The %ROWTYPE attribute provides a record type that represents a row in a database table. The record can store an entire row of data selected from the table or fetched from a cursor or cursor variable. Variables declared using %ROWTYPE are treated like those declared using a datatype name. You can use the %ROWTYPE attribute in variable declarations as a datatype specifier.

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
variable_name table_name%rowtype;

Following is an example to fetch a row using the %rowtype attribute.

xxxxxxxxxx

  select * into emp_row_type from emp where empno ='5';

6
END;

In the above given example, a variable is declared using the %rowtype. Then we have fetched the full row of the employee having empno 5.

Control Statements - Conditional Statements

Control Statements in PL/SQL

Control statements enable us to specify the flow of program control; ie, the order in which the instructions in a program must be executed. They make it possible to make decisions, to perform tasks repeatedly or to jump from one section of code to another.

Just like in programming languages like C and Java ,PL/SQL also offers control statements like conditional statements ,loops and Jump Statements

PL/SQL supports the programming language features like conditional statements and iterative statements. Its programming constructs are similar to how you use them in programming languages like Java and C.

Conditional Statements in PL/SQL

IF ELSIF ELSE:

The IF-ELSIF-ELSE statement allows you to choose between several alternatives.Its just like IF-ELSE statement in programming languages like C and Java. An IF-THEN statement can be followed by an optional ELSIF...ELSE statement. The ELSIF clause lets us add additional conditions.

While using the IF-ELSIF-ELSE statements there are a few points to keep in mind.

  • It's ELSIF, not ELSEIF.
  • An IF-THEN statement can have zero or one ELSE's and it must come after any ELSIF's.
  • An IF-THEN statement can have zero to many ELSIF's and they must come before the ELSE.
  • Once an ELSIF succeeds, none of the remaining ELSIF's or ELSE's will be tested.
  • The IF-ELSIF-ELSE statement ends with an END IF; clause.If the END IF clause is not present the compiler will throw an error.

Following is the syntax on how to use the IF-ELSIF-ELSE statement

xxxxxxxxxx
7
1
IF CONDITION THEN
2
    <STATEMENTS>
3
ELSIF CONDITION THEN
4
    <STATEMENTS>
5
ELSE
6
    <STATEMENTS>
7
END IF;

Below given is an example on how to use the IF-ELSIF-ELSE statement in a PL/SQL block:

        DBMS_output.put_line('In Else');

    END IF;
11

Control Statements - Loops

There may be situations where statements need to be iterated until a condition is met.In that case PL/SQL offers loops. The concept of loops is exactly the same as other programming languages.PL/SQL offers 3 types of loops:

  1. BASIC loop
  2. WHILE loop
  3. FOR loop

So lets learn about these one by one! Let's start with the basic loop.

Basic Loop

In this loop,statements are enclosed between the LOOP and the END LOOP statements. At each iteration, the sequence of statements is executed and then control resumes at the top of the loop.To end the iteration of the BASIC loop , the EXIT statement is used to break out of the loop.

Given below is the syntax of using a basic loop:

xxxxxxxxxx
6
1
LOOP
2
    <<statements>>;
3
    [ [ IF CONDITION THEN EXIT; END IF   ]
4
    /* OR
5
    [ EXIT WHEN condition; ] ] */
6
END LOOP;

   END LOOP;
11

For loop is used when a set of statements is to be executed for a predetermined number of times. The loop is iterated between the start and end integer values. The counter is always incremented by 1 and once the counter reaches the end integer, the loop ends.

Control Statements - Jump Statements

A GOTO statement in PL/SQL programming language provides an unconditional jump from the GOTO to a labeled statement in the same subprogram.

Following is the syntax to use the GO TO statement

xxxxxxxxxx
4
1
GOTO label_name;
2
 
3
<<label_name>>
4
<<STATEMENTS>>

To see the working of a GOTO statement, let’s see at the below example:

xxxxxxxxxx
14
1
DECLARE
2
   myvar number := 10;
3
BEGIN
4
 
5
   IF myvar > 5 THEN
6
       goto update_myvar;
7
   ELSE
8
       dbms_output.put_line('Else');   
9
   END IF;
10
  
11
   <<update_myvar>>
12
   myvar:=40;
13
   dbms_output.put_line('myvar updated to '||myvar);   
14
END;

When the control goes the goto statement. After that the control goes to <<update_myvar>> and after that the statements are executed. Output as follows:

xxxxxxxxxx
3
1
myvar updated to 40
2
 
3
PL/SQL procedure successfully completed.

There are some restrictions while using the GOTO statement -

  • A GOTO statement cannot branch into an IF statement, CASE statement, LOOP statement or sub-block.
  • A GOTO statement cannot branch from one IF statement clause to another or from one CASE statement WHEN clause to another.
  • A GOTO statement cannot branch from an outer block into a sub-block (i.e., an inner BEGIN-END block).
  • A GOTO statement cannot branch out of a subprogram. To end a subprogram early, either use the RETURN statement or have GOTO branch to a place right before the end of the subprogram.
  • A GOTO statement cannot branch from an exception handler back into the current BEGIN-END block. However, a GOTO statement can branch from an exception handler into an enclosing block.

PL/SQL: Introduction to Exception Handling

Errors are the conditions which cannot get recovered by any handling techniques. Error is a condition that we don’t handle when it occurs whereas Exception is a condition that deals with the errors and that can be handled explicitlt.PL/SQL also supports Programming to catch such conditions using Exception block and an appropriate action is taken against the error condition.

There are two categories of Exceptions in PL/SQL:

  1. System-Defined:- Already defined in Oracle.
  2. User-Defined :- Defined Explicitly By User.

Following is the general syntax of handling exceptions using Exception Block in PL/SQL

xxxxxxxxxx
10
1
DECLARE
2
    <Declaration>
3
BEGIN
4
        <Executable>
5
    EXCEPTION
6
            When <Exception_name> then <output1>;
7
           When <Exception_name> then <output2>;
8
           When <Exception_name> then <output3>;
9
           When OTHERS then <output>;
10
END;

Every Exception in Oracle has something called SQLCODE and SQLERRM. SQLCODE returns the number code of the most recent exception.The number that SQLCODE returns is negative unless the Oracle error is no data found, in which case SQLCODE returns +100.

The SQLERRM returns the error message associated with the most recently raised error exception. This should only be used within the Exception Handling section of the code.

 

PRE-DEFINED EXCEPTIONS:

There are many predefined exceptions available in PL/SQL which are raised whenever any database rule is violated by the programs.

For example, NO_DATA_FOUND is a pre-defined exception which is raised when a SELECT INTO statement returns no rows.

Following is a list of some important pre-defined exceptions

CASE_NOT_FOUND: It is raised when none of the choices in the “WHEN” clause of a CASE statement is selected, and there is no else clause. It’s SQL-Code is -6592

VALUE_ERROR: It is raised when an arithmetic, conversion, truncation, or size-constraint error occurs. For example, when your program selects a column value into a character variable, if the value is longer than the declared length of the variable, PL/SQL aborts the assignment and raises VALUE_ERROR. In procedural statements, VALUE_ERROR is raised if the conversion of a character string into a number fails. It’s SQL-Code is -6502

ZERO_DIVISION: It is raised when an attempt is made to divide a number by ZERO. It’s SQL-Code is -1476

DUP_VAL_ON_INDEX: It is raised when a duplicate value is inserted in a column with a unique index. It’s SQL-Code is -1

INVALID_NUMBER : It is raised when a conversion of character string into a number fails because the string does not represent a valid number. It’s SQL-Code is -1722

NO_DATA_FOUND : It is raised when no data for a query is found. It’s SQL-Code is +100

TOO_MANY_ROWS: It is raised when a SELECT INTO statement returns more than one row. It’s SQL-Code is -1422.

 

Let’s see an example that illustrates on how to handle an exception

xxxxxxxxxx
12
1
DECLARE 
2
    a number:= 10;
3
    b number:= 0;
4
    c number;
5
BEGIN 
6
    c := a/b;
7
    dbms_output.put_line(c);
8
    EXCEPTION 
9
        WHEN ZERO_DIVIDE THEN 
10
            dbms_output.put_line(SQLCODE||' '||SQLERRM);
11
END;
12
/

2
 
3
PL/SQL procedure successfully completed.

        dbms_output.put_line(SQLCODE||' '||SQLERRM);

 

USER DEFINED EXCEPTIONS:

In Oracle, other than the predefined exceptions, the programmer can create their own exception and handle them. They can be created at a subprogram level in the declaration part. These exceptions are visible only in that subprogram. So let’s see how to create a user-defined exception.

2

EXCEPTION

8
        <STATEMENTS>
9
END;
10
/

In the above syntax, the variable 'exception_name' is defined as 'EXCEPTION' type.

We use the keyword 'RAISE' followed by the exception name to raise that particular user-defined/predefined exception.

So lets see an example on how to create an user-defined Exception

xxxxxxxxxx

In the above example an exception named my_exception is created.

Note: The exception created doesn’t have a SQLCODE or a SQLERRM. So it will have the default value of SQLCODE as 1 and SQLERRM as User-Defined Exception.

To assign a SQLCODE to this exception we’ll use PRAGMA EXCEPTION_INIT statement and show a SQLERRM we’ll use raise_application_error statement.

PRAGMA EXCEPTION_INIT

Pragma Exception_Init is a two part statement where the first part is made up of the keyword PRAGMA and the second part is the Exception_Init call.

A pragma is a compiler directive which indicates that the Statements followed by keyword PRAGMA is a compiler directive statement this means that the statement will be processed at the compile time & not at the runtime.

Exception_init helps you in associating an exception name with an Oracle error number. In other words we can say that using Exception_Init you can name the exception.

Below given is the syntax on how to use the PRAGMA EXCEPTION_INIT statement,

xxxxxxxxxx

Raise_application_error

The raise_application_error is a built-in procedure that allows the developer to associate his/her own error message to an oracle error number. It helps in returning a custom error to your application so that you can avoid returning unhandled exceptions. Thus, the message given by a developer acts as an oracle error message here.

Below given is the syntax of the raise_application_error statement

Introduction to Triggers

Trigger is a database object that is executed automatically when an INSERT, UPDATE or DELETE statement is issued against the associated table.

Triggers are database callback functions, which are automatically performed/invoked when a specified database event occurs.

Triggers are useful in many cases such as the following:

  • Enforcing complex business rules that cannot be established using integrity constraints such as UNIQUE, NOT NULL, and CHECK.
  • Preventing invalid transactions.
  • Gathering statistical information on table accesses.
  • Generating value automatically for derived columns.

Creating Triggers

Below is the general syntax for creating a trigger

xxxxxxxxxx
12
1
CREATE [OR REPLACE] TRIGGER trigger_name
2
{BEFORE | AFTER } triggering_event ON table_name
3
[FOR EACH ROW]
4
[WHEN condition]
5
DECLARE
6
    declaration statements
7
BEGIN
8
    executable statements
9
EXCEPTION
10
    exception_handling statements
11
END;
12
/

Let’s study the syntax in a detailed manner

The CREATE keyword specifies that a new trigger is to be created. The OR REPLACE keywords are optional. They are used to modify an existing trigger. If an already existing trigger with the name trigger_name in the database, the OR REPLACE keyword replaces the previous definition of the trigger with the current definition provided.

The BEFORE or AFTER option specifies when the trigger fires, either before or after a triggering event e.g., INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE. We can add multiple events on which the trigger fires using the OR clause.

The table_name is the name of the table associated with the trigger.

The clause FOR EACH ROW specifies that the trigger is a row-level trigger. A row-level trigger fires once for each row inserted, updated, or deleted.

And then is the trigger body which contains the code to execute whenever the trigger is fired.

-> To create a trigger on the employees table that runs after every insert and update statement,

xxxxxxxxxx

3
    before insert or update
4
    on employees
5
begin
6
    null; /* Just for creating an empty valid trigger */
7
end; 
8
/

The above example creates a trigger and whenever data is inserted into the table that trigger will execute.

Alter Trigger

Unlike other ALTER commands, the ALTER TRIGGER statement does not change the definition or structure of a trigger. That is done using the CREATE OR REPLACE TRIGGER statement.

ALTER TRIGGER statements enables or disables a trigger. ENABLE a trigger means that the trigger will fire automatically whenever the statement included in it's definition is executed. DISABLE is the opposite of ENABLE. When disabled the trigger will not fire automatically whenever the statement included in it's definition is executed.

Syntax for ALTER TRIGGER is

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
ALTER TRIGGER trigger_name [ENABLE|DISABLE];

For example to disable the trigger

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
ALTER TRIGGER emp_trigger DISABLE;

To enable the trigger

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
ALTER TRIGGER emp_trigger ENABLE;

Introduction to Cursors

Whenever a statement is executed in Oracle, Oracle creates a memory area , known as the context area, for processing the SQL statement. This context area contains all the information needed for processing the statement, for example, number of rows processed while executing the statement etc.

Cursors are basically pointers to context areas. In PL/SQL we can control the context area through cursors. A cursor holds the rows (one or more) returned by a SQL statement. The set of rows the cursor holds is referred to as the active set.

In Oracle , there are 2 types of cursors:

  1. Implicit Cursors
  2. Explicit Cursors

 

Implicit Cursors

Implicit cursors are automatically defined by the oracle engine. These cursors are created whenever an SQL statement is executed. Implicit Cursors cannot be controlled by the programmer.

Whenever a DML command (insert, update,delete ) is executed, oracle issues an implicit cursor with it.

For INSERT operations, the cursor holds the data that needs to be inserted. For UPDATE and DELETE operations, the cursor identifies the rows that would be affected.

In PL/SQL, the most recent implicit cursor can be referred by SQL cursor. The SQL cursor has already defined attributes such as %ROWCOUNT,%FOUND etc.

Following are the most used attributes of the SQL cursor

  1. %FOUND: Returns TRUE if an INSERT, UPDATE, or DELETE statement affected one or more rows or a SELECT INTO statement returned one or more rows. Otherwise, it returns FALSE
  2. %NOTFOUND: It is the opposite of the %FOUND attribute. It returns TRUE if no row is affected when the DML command is issued. Otherwise, it returns FALSE.
  3. %ISOPEN: This attribute returns always FALSE for implicit cursors. This is because , oracle closes the cursors automatically after executing the SQL statement
  4. %ROWCOUNT: Returns the number of rows affected by the SQL statement when executed.

The SQL Cursor attribute can be accessed through the following syntax,

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SQL%attribute_name

Now, lets see an example of how to use the implicit cursors

xxxxxxxxxx
15
1
-- Table already create as per given definition
2
-- create table students(roll INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,name VARCHAR(50));
3
 
4
DECLARE 
5
  rows_affected number(2);
6
BEGIN
7
   UPDATE students SET roll = roll + 1000;
8
   IF sql%notfound THEN
9
       dbms_output.put_line('no rows affected');
10
   ELSIF sql%found THEN
11
       rows_affected := sql%rowcount;
12
       dbms_output.put_line(  rows_affected || ' rows affected ');
13
   END IF; 
14
END;
15
/

Explicit Cursors

Explicit Cursors are defined by the programmer and the programmer has more control over the context area. An explicit cursor must be declared in the DECLARE section of a PL/SQL block

Below is the syntax for creating an explicit cursor:

CURSOR cursor_name IS select_statement;

There are 4 steps through the lifetime of cursor.They are :

  1. Declaring a cursor: Declaring the cursor simply means to create one named context area for the 'SELECT' statement that is defined in the declaration part. The name of this context area is the same as the cursor name.
  2. Opening a cursor: Opening the cursor will instruct the PL/SQL to allocate the memory for this cursor. It will make the cursor ready to fetch the records
  3. Fetching the cursor values: In this process, the 'SELECT' statement is executed and the rows fetched are stored in the allocated memory. These are now called active sets. Fetching data from the cursor is a record-level activity that means we can access the data in a record-by-record way.
  4. Each fetch statement will fetch one active set and hold the information of that particular record. This statement is the same as the 'SELECT' statement that fetches the record and assigns to the variable in the 'INTO' clause, but it will not throw any exceptions.
  5. Closing a cursor: Once all the record is fetched now, we need to close the cursor so that the memory allocated to this context area will be released.

Following is the syntax for using a cursor:

xxxxxxxxxx
8
1
DECLARE
2
   CURSOR <cursor_name> IS <<select_statement>>
3
BEGIN
4
   OPEN <cursor_name>;
5
   FETCH <cursor_name> INTO <variables>;
6
   CLOSE <cursor_name>;
7
END;
8
/

Now , let’s see an example that shows the working of an explicit cursors,

xxxxxxxxxx
12
1
-- create table students(roll INTEGER PRIMARY KEY,name VARCHAR(50));
2
  
3
DECLARE
4
   CURSOR studs_cursor IS select name from students where roll = 7;
5
   stud_name students.name %type;
6
BEGIN
7
   OPEN studs_cursor;
8
   FETCH  studs_cursor INTO stud_name;
9
   dbms_output.put_line(stud_name);
10
   CLOSE studs_cursor;
11
END;
12
/

The Cursor FOR loop

FOR LOOP statements can be used for working with cursors. The cursor name is given instead of range limit in the FOR loop statement so that the loop will work from the first record of the cursor to the last record of the cursor. The cursor variable, opening of cursor, fetching and closing of the cursor will be done implicitly by the FOR loop.

Syntax:

xxxxxxxxxx
8
1

2
   CURSOR <cursor_name> IS <SELECT statement>;
3
BEGIN
4

5
   LOOP
6
       <<statements>>
7
   END LOOP;
8
END;

In the above syntax, the declaration part contains the declaration of the cursor. The cursor is created for the 'SELECT' statement that is given in the cursor declaration. In the execution part, the declared cursor is set up in the FOR loop and the loop variable 'i' will behave as a cursor variable in this case.

Below is an example to use cursor FOR loop,

Procedures

Just like functions , A procedure(or a stored procedure) is a subroutine (like a subprogram) in a regular scripting language, stored in a database. It is basically a function with some restrictions. A procedure has a name, a parameter list, and SQL statement(s). Almost all relational database systems support stored procedures.

The major difference is that User defined functions can be used like any other expression within SQL statements, whereas stored procedures must be invoked using the CALL statement. Functions can return any value whereas procedures don't return anything.

To create a procedure , CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE statement is used:

xxxxxxxxxx
8
1
CREATE [ OR REPLACE ] PROCEDURE procedure_name  (parameter_name [IN | OUT | INOUT ] parameter_data_type,... )  
2
IS  
3

Functions

Just like any programming language Oracle also supports functions. Functions are just a set of statements that can be reused again and again. We don't have to write the code again and again to perform the same task.They are mainly subprograms that are designed to perform a particular task regardless of the parameters passed to them.

We have learnt that there are many built-in functions available provided by the database. Every RDBMS provides the same types of functions, the only difference is the functions’ calling syntax. Every RDBMS has its own function definition, it may or may not be present in other databases. For example MySQL has a function called STRCMP but oracle doesn’t have it. Moreover both the databases have a function called UPPER to convert a string to Uppercase.

Oracle also offers the developer to design a custom function depending on the needs of the developer. The general syntax of creating a function is given below:

While passing parameters in functions, it has the following three modes.

  1. IN: It is the default mode. It takes a parameter as input. It is to be defined and the calling program has to pass an argument to the stored procedure. This parameter's value is always protected.This means that whether the value of parameter is changed inside the procedure or not, its original value is retained after the procedure ends
  2. OUT: It is used to pass a parameter as output. Its value can be changed inside the stored procedure, and the changed value is passed back to the calling program. Note that OUT parameter's value cannot be accessed initially in the procedure.
  3. INOUT: It is a combination of IN and OUT parameters. It means the calling program can pass the argument, and the procedure can modify the INOUT parameter, and then pass the new value back to the calling program.

 

To call a function just use a select expression with the function name. Syntax of calling a function is given below:

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
SELECT mySum(10,20) from DUAL;

The above code gives an output of 30.

Packages in Oracle

 

PL/SQL package is a logical grouping of a related subprogram (procedure/function) into a single element. A Package is compiled and stored as a database object that can be used later.

Reason to use packages

  • Modularity: Packages let you encapsulate logically related types, variables, constants, subprograms, cursors, and exceptions in named PL/SQL modules. You can make each package easy to understand, and make the interfaces between packages simple, clear, and well defined. This practice aids application development.
  • Easier Application Design: When designing an application, all you need initially is the interface information in the package specifications. You can code and compile specifications without their bodies. Next, you can compile standalone subprograms that reference the packages. You need not fully define the package bodies until you are ready to complete the application.
  • Hidden Implementation Details: Packages let you share your interface information in the package specification, and hide the implementation details in the package body.
  • Added Functionality: Package public variables and cursors can persist for the life of a session. They can be shared by all subprograms that run in the environment. They let you maintain data across transactions without storing it in the database.
  • Better Performance: The first time you invoke a package subprogram, Oracle Database loads the whole package into memory. Subsequent invocations of other subprograms in the same package require no disk I/O.

 

A PL/SQL package consists of 2 components

  • Package Specification
  • Package Body

 

Package Specification

A package specification declares public items. The scope of a public item is the schema of the package. A public item is visible everywhere in the schema. To reference a public item that is in scope but not visible, qualify it with the package name.

Each public item declaration has all information needed to use the item. For example, suppose that a package specification declares the function factorial this way:

 

xxxxxxxxxx
1
1
FUNCTION factorial (n INTEGER) RETURN INTEGER; -- returns n!

 

The declaration shows that factorial needs one argument of type INTEGER and returns a value of type INTEGER, which invokers must know to invoke factorial. Invokers need not know how factorial is implemented (for example, whether it is iterative or recursive).

Below are a few characteristics of the Package specification.

  • The elements which are all declared in the specification can be accessed from outside of the package. Such elements are known as a public element.
  • The package specification is a standalone element that means it can exist alone without a package body.
  • Whenever a package has been referred to, an instance of the package is created for that particular session.
  • After the instance is created for a session, all the package elements that are initiated in that instance are valid until the end of the session.

Syntax

xxxxxxxxxx
4
1
CREATE [OR REPLACE] PACKAGE <package_name> 
2
IS
3
<sub_program and public element declaration>
4
END <package name>

 

Package Body

It consists of the definition of all the elements that are present in the package specification. It can also have a definition of elements that are not declared in the specification, these elements are called private elements and can be called only from inside the package.

Below are characteristics of a package body.

  • It should contain definitions for all the subprograms/cursors that have been declared in the specification.
  • It can also have more subprograms or other elements that are not declared in specification. These are called private elements.
  • It is a dependable object, and it depends on package specification.
  • The state of the package body becomes 'Invalid' whenever the specification is compiled. Therefore, it needs to be recompiled each time after the compilation of specification.
  • The private elements should be defined first before they are used in the package body.
  • The first part of the package is the global declaration part. This includes variables, cursors and private elements (forward declaration) that is visible to the entire package.
  • The last part of the package is the Package initialization part that executes one time whenever a package is referred for the first time in the session.

Syntax:

xxxxxxxxxx
8
1
CREATE [OR REPLACE] PACKAGE BODY <package_name>
2
IS
3
<global_declaration part>
4
<Private element definition>
5
<sub_program and public element definition>
6
.
7
<Package Initialization> 
8
END <package_name>
